<DOC><DOCNO> AP890720-0083 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-20-89 1035EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-SouthAfrica-Mozambique     07-20 0308</FIRST><SECOND>PM-South Africa-Mozambique,0319</SECOND><HEAD>Mozambique Refugees Flee Clash in Which Dozens Reported Killed</HEAD><DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Police today said 567Mozambican refugees fled across the border to escape a gunbattlebetween guerrillas and government troops in which dozens of peoplewere reported killed.   One person drowned in the Komati River while trying to reachSouth Africa, said police Capt. Ruben Bloomberg at policeheadquarters in Pretoria.   Bloomberg said the number of people killed on the other side ofthe border, at Ressano Garcia, was unknown.   But government-run Radio South Africa said witnesses reporteddozens of people were killed when Mozambique National Resistanceguerrillas fired small arms and mortars at Mozambican governmentsoldiers in Ressano Garcia.   Refugees frequently have fled across the river into South Africaat the Ressano Garcia border point when attacked by guerrillas.   Bloomberg was quoted by the South African Press Association assaying the refugees were held overnight and released today withoutbeing charged. He said most had returned to Mozambique.   Bloomberg said the cause of the Wednesday night gunbattle wasunknown.   The Noticias newspaper in Mozambique reported that the guerrillaskilled 82 peasants, including children, and wounded 111 in an attackTuesday night on Sanguane village, in the southern province of Gaza.   The newspaper said some people escaped and notified soldiersnearby, who killed 20 guerrillas at Sanguane and captured someweapons.   The Ressano Garcia fighting occurred a few hours after the leaderof South Africa's governing National Party, F.W. de Klerk, returnedfrom a meeting in Maputo with Mozambican President Joaquim Chissano.   They discussed Mozambican accusations that the guerrillas stillreceive support and supplies from inside South Africa.   Chissano said he accepted that the South African government andmilitary were no longer giving such support, and de Klerk said theSouth African government would investigate any specific details thatMozambique provided.</TEXT></DOC>